                <p>
                    "It is red or not red" is always true; "It is both red and
                    not red" is always false.
                </p>

                <table>
                    <tr>
                        <th class="table-head" colspan="1">
                            De Morgan's Laws
                        </th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            &not;(<i>p</i> &and; <i>q</i>) &equiv;
                            &not;<i>p</i> &or; &not;<i>q</i>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            &not;(<i>p</i> &or; <i>q</i>) &equiv;
                            &not;<i>p</i> &and; &not;<i>q</i>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                <p>
                    Row 1: "It's not raining and sunny" means that it is not
                    raining <i>or</i> it's not sunny.
                    <br />
                    Row 2: "It's not raining or sunny" means that it is not
                    raining <i>and</i> it's not sunny.
